    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Power plants producing electricity by utilizing temperature differentials between surface water heated by the sun and deep cold water pumped to the surface. Power plants producing electricity by utilizing temperature differentials between surface water heated by the sun and deep cold water pumped to the surface.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000027831/McGraw-Hill Encyclopedia of Science and Technology (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Planta motriz que produce electricidad empleando las diferenciales térmicas que existen entre el agua superficial calentada por el sol y el agua fría de la zona profunda bombeada hacia la superficie.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Elektriciteitscentrales die elektriciteit produceren door gebruik te maken van het temperatuurverschil tussen oppervlaktewater dat wordt verwarmd door de zon en koud water uit de diepte dat naar de oppervlakte wordt gepompt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
